WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.680
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:04.280 --> 00:07.720
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:08.500 --> 00:15.040
For more information or to volunteer please visit LibriVox.org.

00:15.040 --> 00:19.100
Recording by Marlo Dianne

00:19.100 --> 00:24.460
ForbiddenDragon.blogspot.com

00:25.000 --> 00:27.020
Anne of Green Gables

00:27.300 --> 00:30.160
by Lucy Maud Montgomery

00:31.360 --> 00:32.940
Chapter 22

00:33.460 --> 00:36.140
Anne is invited out to tea.

00:38.740 --> 00:42.140
And what are your eyes popping out of your head about now?

00:42.720 --> 00:47.020
asked Marilla, when Anne had just come in from a run to the post office.

00:47.660 --> 00:50.040
Have you discovered another kindred spirit?

00:52.140 --> 00:58.000
Excitement hung around Anne like a garment, shone in her eyes, kindled in every feature.

00:58.900 --> 01:02.900
She had come dancing up the lane like a windblown sprite

01:02.900 --> 01:07.420
through the mellow sunshine and lazy shadows of the August evening.

01:09.440 --> 01:13.120
No, Marilla, but oh, what do you think?

01:13.320 --> 01:16.340
I'm invited to tea at the man's tomorrow afternoon.

01:16.880 --> 01:19.520
Mrs. Allen left the letter for me at the post office.

01:19.960 --> 01:21.440
Just look at it, Marilla.

01:21.900 --> 01:24.840
Miss Anne Shirley, Green Gables.

01:25.300 --> 01:27.840
That is the first time I was ever called Miss.

01:28.480 --> 01:30.160
Such a thrill it gave me.

01:30.160 --> 01:34.120
I shall cherish it forever among my choicest treasures.

01:36.120 --> 01:40.920
Mrs. Allen told me she meant to have all the members of her Sunday school class to tea in turn,

01:41.700 --> 01:45.800
said Marilla, regarding the wonderful event very coolly.

01:46.480 --> 01:48.620
You needn't get in such a fever over it.

01:48.940 --> 01:51.060
Do learn to take things calmly, child.

01:53.120 --> 01:56.880
For Anne to take things calmly would have been to change her nature.

01:56.880 --> 02:03.060
All spirit and fire and dew as she was, the pleasures and pains of life

02:03.060 --> 02:05.240
came to her with trebled intensity.

02:06.300 --> 02:09.940
Marilla felt this and was vaguely troubled over it,

02:10.200 --> 02:16.320
realizing that the ups and downs of existence would probably bear hardly on this impulsive soul

02:16.320 --> 02:21.680
and not sufficiently understanding that the equally great capacity for delight

02:21.680 --> 02:23.480
might more than compensate.

02:25.040 --> 02:31.600
Therefore Marilla conceived it to be her duty to drill Anne into a tranquil uniformity of disposition

02:31.600 --> 02:37.560
as impossible and alien to her as to a dancing sunbeam in one of the brook shallows.

02:38.360 --> 02:43.000
She did not make much headway, as she sorrowfully admitted to herself.

02:43.760 --> 02:49.340
The downfall of some dear hope or plan plunged Anne into depths of affliction.

02:49.340 --> 02:55.020
The fulfillment thereof exalted her to dizzying realms of delight.

02:55.840 --> 03:00.380
Marilla had almost begun to despair of ever fashioning this waif of the world

03:00.380 --> 03:05.740
into her model little girl of demure manners and prim deportment.

03:06.180 --> 03:10.400
Neither would she believe that she really liked Anne much better as she was.

03:12.220 --> 03:15.380
Anne went to bed that night speechless with misery,

03:15.380 --> 03:21.840
because Matthew had said the wind was round northeast and he feared it would be a rainy day tomorrow.

03:22.720 --> 03:26.580
The rustle of the poplar leaves around the house worried her.

03:27.080 --> 03:33.140
It sounded so like pattering raindrops and the full faraway roar of the gulf,

03:33.500 --> 03:39.600
to which she listened delightly at other times, loving its strange, sonorous, haunting rhythm,

03:39.600 --> 03:48.220
now seemed like a prophecy of storm and disaster to a small maiden who particularly wanted a fine day.

03:49.280 --> 03:51.860
Anne thought that the morning would never come.

03:53.500 --> 04:00.580
But all things have an end, even nights before the day in which you were invited to take tea at the manse.

04:01.140 --> 04:08.020
The morning, in spite of Matthew's predictions, was fine, and Anne's spirits soared to their highest.

04:09.260 --> 04:15.400
Oh, Marilla, there is something in me today that makes me just love everybody I see,

04:15.880 --> 04:18.600
she exclaimed as she washed the breakfast dishes.

04:19.120 --> 04:23.600
You don't know how good I feel. Wouldn't it be nice if it could last?

04:24.120 --> 04:29.040
I believe I could be a model child if I were just invited out to tea every day.

04:29.440 --> 04:35.080
But, oh, Marilla, it's a solemn occasion, too. I feel so anxious.

04:35.080 --> 04:40.240
What if I shouldn't behave properly? You know I have never had tea at a manse before,

04:40.440 --> 04:43.180
and I'm not sure that I know all the rules of etiquette,

04:43.460 --> 04:48.240
although I've been studying the rules given in the etiquette department of the family herald ever since I came here.

04:48.680 --> 04:53.620
I'm so afraid I'll do something silly or forget to do something I should do.

04:54.260 --> 04:59.160
Would it be good manners to take a second helping of anything if you wanted it very much?

05:00.540 --> 05:04.390
The trouble with you, Anne, is that you're thinking too much about yourself.

05:05.020 --> 05:08.920
You should just think of Mrs. Allen and what would be nice as the most agreeable to her,

05:09.580 --> 05:15.260
said Marilla, hitting for once in her life on a very sound and pithy piece of advice.

05:15.700 --> 05:18.200
Anne instantly recognized this.

05:19.660 --> 05:24.020
You are right, Marilla. I'll try not to think about myself at all.

05:25.260 --> 05:30.400
Anne evidently got through her visit without any serious breach of etiquette,

05:30.520 --> 05:35.320
for she came home through the twilight, under a great high-sprung sky,

05:36.240 --> 05:42.900
gloried over with trails of saffron and rosy cloud, in a beautified state of mind,

05:43.440 --> 05:50.320
and told Marilla all about it happily, sitting on the big red sandstone slab at the kitchen door,

05:50.320 --> 05:54.580
with her tired curly head in Marilla's gingham lap.

05:56.040 --> 06:00.160
A cool wind was blowing down over the long harvest fields,

06:00.480 --> 06:05.580
from the rims of furry western hills and whistling through the poplars.

06:06.500 --> 06:13.720
One clear star hung over the orchard, and the fireflies were flitting over in lovers' lane,

06:13.720 --> 06:17.980
in and out among the ferns and rustling boughs.

06:18.660 --> 06:24.640
Anne watched them as she talked, and somehow felt that wind and stars and fireflies

06:24.640 --> 06:31.100
were all tangled up together into something unutterably sweet and enchanting.

06:32.620 --> 06:36.800
Oh, Marilla, I've had a most fascinating time.

06:37.260 --> 06:42.000
I feel that I have not lived in vain, and I shall always feel like that,

06:42.000 --> 06:45.460
even if I should never be invited to tea at a manse again.

06:46.060 --> 06:49.400
When I got there, Mrs. Allen met me at the door.

06:49.760 --> 06:53.520
She was dressed in the sweetest dress of pale pink organdy,

06:53.820 --> 06:59.400
with dozens of frills and elbow sleeves, and she looked just like a seraph.

06:59.820 --> 07:03.500
I really think I'd like to be a minister's wife when I grow up, Marilla.

07:04.320 --> 07:09.660
A minister mightn't mind my red hair, because he wouldn't be thinking of such worldly things.

07:09.660 --> 07:15.020
But then, of course, one would have to be naturally good, and I'll never be that.

07:15.140 --> 07:17.900
So I suppose there's no use in thinking about it.

07:18.500 --> 07:21.920
Some people are naturally good, you know, and others are not.

07:22.220 --> 07:23.340
I'm one of the others.

07:24.020 --> 07:26.640
Mrs. Lynn says I'm full of original sin.

07:26.980 --> 07:32.840
No matter how hard I try to be good, I can never make such a success of it as those who are naturally good.

07:34.020 --> 07:36.720
It's a good deal like geometry, I expect.

07:37.360 --> 07:40.860
But don't you think that trying so hard ought to count for something?

07:42.240 --> 07:44.960
Mrs. Allen is one of the naturally good people.

07:45.400 --> 07:47.040
I love her passionately.

07:47.500 --> 07:53.500
You know there are some people, like Matthew and Mrs. Allen, that you can love right off without any trouble.

07:54.140 --> 07:59.260
And there are others, like Mrs. Lynn, that you have to try very hard to love.

07:59.980 --> 08:05.400
You know you ought to love them, because they know so much and are such active workers in the church,

08:05.400 --> 08:09.980
but you have to keep reminding yourself of it all the time, or else you forget.

08:10.800 --> 08:14.980
There was another little girl at the Man's to Tea from the White Sands Sunday School.

08:15.380 --> 08:18.540
Her name was Laurette Bradley, and she was a very nice little girl.

08:18.800 --> 08:20.940
Not exactly a kid in spirit, you know.

08:21.380 --> 08:23.160
But still, very nice.

08:23.600 --> 08:28.140
We had an elegant tea, and I think I kept all the rules of etiquette pretty well.

08:28.560 --> 08:32.860
After tea, Mrs. Allen played and sang, and she got Laurette and me to sing, too.

08:32.860 --> 08:37.800
Mrs. Allen says I have a good voice, and she says I must sing in the Sunday School Choir after this.

08:38.400 --> 08:40.680
You can't think how I was thrilled at the mere thought.

08:41.320 --> 08:48.000
I've longed so to sing in the Sunday School Choir as Dana does, but I feared it was an honor I could never aspire to.

08:48.500 --> 08:53.520
Laurette had to go home early, because there's a big concert in the White Sands Hotel tonight, and her sister is to recite it.

08:54.160 --> 08:59.660
Laurette says that the Americans at the hotel give a concert every fortnight in aid of the Charlottetown Hospital,

08:59.660 --> 09:02.620
and they ask lots of the White Sands people to recite.

09:03.560 --> 09:06.260
Laurette said she expected to be asked herself some day.

09:06.620 --> 09:08.500
I just gazed at her in awe.

09:09.000 --> 09:11.920
After she had gone, Mrs. Allen and I had a heart-to-heart talk.

09:12.160 --> 09:19.480
I told her everything about Mrs. Thomas and the twins and Katie Maurice and Violetta and coming to Green Gables and my troubles over geometry,

09:19.580 --> 09:20.920
and would you believe it, Marilla?

09:21.300 --> 09:24.120
Mrs. Allen told me she was adept at geometry, too.

09:24.440 --> 09:26.400
You don't know how that encouraged me.

09:26.400 --> 09:29.140
Mrs. Lynn came to the man's just before I left.

09:29.440 --> 09:30.940
And what do you think, Marilla?

09:31.160 --> 09:34.560
The trustees have hired a new teacher, and it's a lady.

09:34.980 --> 09:37.160
Her name is Miss Muriel Stacey.

09:37.640 --> 09:39.320
Isn't that a romantic name?

09:39.620 --> 09:44.920
Mrs. Lynn says they've never had a female teacher in Avonlea before, and she thinks it's a dangerous innovation,

09:45.360 --> 09:48.180
but I think it'll be splendid to have a lady teacher.

09:48.420 --> 09:52.280
And I really don't see how I'm going to live through the two weeks before school begins.

09:52.280 --> 09:55.420
I'm so impatient to see her.

